{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3539204,"name":"Nicollas","username":"Nicollas","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/n/59ef9b/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-02-25T13:23:32.057Z","cooked":"<p>Hello, our team is currently using the Through Bore encoder from REV, and we would like to know if there is any way to use the absolute mode so that it can identify rotations above 360 degrees, without resetting the encoder from 0.9 to 0. We are currently considering using the Alternate mode of the encoder, but we really don’t understand its functionality. Could someone explain it to us?</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":4,"updated_at":"2025-02-25T13:23:32.057Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":26,"reads":64,"readers_count":63,"score":142.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":493116,"topic_slug":"absolute-mode-and-alternate-mode-on-rev-through-bore-encoder","display_username":"Nicollas","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":73398,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":""},"post_url":"/t/absolute-mode-and-alternate-mode-on-rev-through-bore-encoder/493116/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3539209,"name":"John Slagel","username":"Novicaine","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/n/ac8455/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-02-25T13:30:57.592Z","cooked":"<p>I don’t know the answer to your question about the Alternate mode, but what we did to track multiple rotations using a Through Bore encoder connected to a Spark Max Alternate Encoder board, was to set the encoder rotation scale to 0…1 and then watch for “rollover” in the periodic function. When rollover occurs, increment (or decrement) a global counter. See the code in the <code>periodic</code> function:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">// Copyright (c) FIRST and other WPILib contributors.
// Open Source Software; you can modify and/or share it under the terms of
// the WPILib BSD license file in the root directory of this project.

package frc.robot.subsystems;

import com.revrobotics.AbsoluteEncoder;
import com.revrobotics.spark.SparkBase.PersistMode;
import com.revrobotics.spark.SparkBase.ResetMode;
import com.revrobotics.spark.SparkLowLevel.MotorType;
import com.revrobotics.spark.SparkMax;
import com.revrobotics.spark.config.SparkBaseConfig.IdleMode;
import com.revrobotics.spark.config.SparkMaxConfig;

import edu.wpi.first.math.MathUtil;
import edu.wpi.first.math.controller.PIDController;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj.smartdashboard.SmartDashboard;
import edu.wpi.first.wpilibj2.command.SubsystemBase;

public class Elevator extends SubsystemBase {
  private final SparkMax m_left,m_right;
  private final SparkMaxConfig m_cfg1,m_cfg2;
  private final AbsoluteEncoder m_turningEncoder;
  private double turningFactor = 1.0;    //2 * Math.PI;
  private double m_lastp = 0;
  private double m_total_trip = 0;

  double min_v = -0.25;
  double max_v = 0.25;
  PIDController pidLoop;


  /** Creates a new Elevator. */
  public Elevator() {
    m_left = new SparkMax(4,MotorType.kBrushless);
    m_cfg1 = new SparkMaxConfig();
    m_cfg1.idleMode(IdleMode.kBrake);
    m_cfg1.inverted(false);
    m_left.configure(m_cfg1, ResetMode.kResetSafeParameters, PersistMode.kPersistParameters);
    m_right = new SparkMax(3, MotorType.kBrushless);
    m_turningEncoder = m_right.getAbsoluteEncoder();

    m_cfg2 = new SparkMaxConfig();
    m_cfg2.idleMode(IdleMode.kBrake);
    m_cfg2.inverted(true);        // This MUST be inverted from the left motor!
    m_cfg2.absoluteEncoder.inverted(true);
    m_cfg2.absoluteEncoder.positionConversionFactor(turningFactor); // degrees
    m_cfg2.absoluteEncoder.velocityConversionFactor(turningFactor / 60.0); // degrees per second
    m_right.configure(m_cfg2, ResetMode.kResetSafeParameters, PersistMode.kPersistParameters);


    m_lastp = m_turningEncoder.getPosition();

    pidLoop = new PIDController(0.2,0,0);   // kp = 8,0,1.3
    pidLoop.setTolerance(0.05);

    // At startup, hold current position
    pidLoop.setSetpoint(getElevatorHeightInches());

  }

  public double getElevatorHeightInches()
  {
      // A counter value of 4.36 = 49" of lift
      return ((m_lastp + m_total_trip)*49.0)/4.36;
  }

  public void setTargetHeightInches(double targetPos)
  {
    pidLoop.setSetpoint(targetPos);
  }

  public void move_setpoint( double v )
  {
    double curTarget = pidLoop.getSetpoint();
    curTarget += v;
    curTarget = MathUtil.clamp(curTarget, 0.1, 51.0);
    setTargetHeightInches(curTarget);
  }

  // This method will be called once per scheduler run
  @Override
  public void periodic() {
    // The encoder reads 0.0-1.0 for each revolution.
    // So this watches for when we roll around and increments
    // or decrements m_total_trip each time it detects this
    // happening.
    double p = m_turningEncoder.getPosition();
    if ( p &lt; 0.25 &amp;&amp; m_lastp &gt; 0.75)  {
      // rolled too high (going up)
      m_total_trip += 1.0;
    } else if ( p &gt; 0.75 &amp;&amp; m_lastp &lt; 0.25 )  {
      // rolled too low (going down)
      m_total_trip -= 1.0;
    }
    m_lastp = p;

    double cpos = getElevatorHeightInches();
    SmartDashboard.putNumber("ElevatorPos",cpos);

    double v = pidLoop.calculate(cpos);
    double v_clamped = MathUtil.clamp(v, min_v, max_v);

    m_left.set(v_clamped);
    m_right.set(v_clamped);
    SmartDashboard.putNumber("Elv.Pid", v_clamped );
    SmartDashboard.putNumber("ElvTarg",pidLoop.getSetpoint() );
  }

}

</code></pre>
